That is not the case in Atlanta. The other factor is the African-American view of divorce. They are aware that divorce is extremely problematic for children, and so are more likely to seek reconciliation.

However, there is one thing that every urban African-American community in America has in common – domestic violence. Teenage boyfriends and girlfriends get into the same kind of arguments. It isn’t even a rarity that you hear of a husband and wife arguments where performance determines whatever disciplinary action they may take, even when the children are hearing things like “You are going to get a beating if you act up” or similar phrases, in front of the children. So neither culture advocates violence at the same level. For every 1 case you hear on the news (in America), in Atlanta, I bet there are 10 cases that are not heard on the airways or in the media. So when we talk about things like marital rape, marital violence etc., I would agree that African American families experience more of it, based upon my personal observations and experiences, both firsthand and anecdotal. However, we see everywhere that within the African Canadian community, these same problems come up, even with gay relationships.
